XSS works because the browser uses &quot;eval&quot; for some attributes, for example <img src=&quot;x&quot; onerror=&quot;alert(1)&quot;>. React never uses eval internally so this class of attacks cannot happen on the server.<p>In order to exploit that vulnerability, improper string concatenation is the most used technique (see SQL injection).<p><pre><code>    var untrustedURL = &#x27;x&quot; onerror=&quot;alert(1)&#x27;;
    document.body.innerHTML += &#x27;<img src=&quot;&#x27; + untrustedURL + &#x27;&quot;>&#x27;;
</code></pre>
In React, you don&#x27;t use string concatenation to build the Virtual DOM. This way you cannot fool React into setting properties that the developer didn&#x27;t explicitly let you.<p><pre><code>    React.renderComponent(document.body, <img src={untrustedURL} />);
    React.renderComponent(document.body, React.DOM.img({src: untrustedURL}));
</code></pre>
Another advantage is that each value in React world is typed. It is either a string which is always escaped, or a component. You cannot turn a string into a component unless the developer explicitly let you.<p>React has been designed with security in mind and prevents by default a large amount of attack vectors that exist in the browser environment.
